class Solution {
    public int removeElement(int[] nums, int val) {
        // ✅ Edge case: if the array is empty, there are no elements to remove
        if (nums.length == 0) {
            return 0;
        }

        // ✅ 'i' is the slow pointer:
        // It represents the position where the next non-val element should be placed.
        int i = 0;

        // ✅ 'j' is the fast pointer:
        // It scans through every element in the array.
        for (int j = 0; j < nums.length; j++) {
            // If the current element is NOT equal to val,
            // we keep it in the array.
            if (nums[j] != val) {
                // Place the non-val element at index 'i'
                nums[i] = nums[j];
                // Move 'i' forward to prepare for the next non-val element.
                i++;
            }
            // If nums[j] == val, skip it (do not copy).
        }

        // ✅ The number of elements that are NOT equal to val is 'i',
        // because 'i' tracks how many valid elements we placed.
        return i; 
    }
}

\\ Time Complexity: 
   𝑂(𝑛) → single pass through the array.

\\ Space Complexity: 
   𝑂(1) → in-place, no extra storage.

\\  Two-pointer technique: Efficient way to filter out unwanted values.
